<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-05-13T10:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-05-13T10:00:00-05:00" n="542" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d542">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 656.119/451</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_PWH1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Page</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-05-13T16:00:00+01:00">
                                        <hi rend="italic">May 13, 1918, 4 p.m.</hi>
                                    </date>
                                    <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 7.15 p.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>10022. War Trade Board [from <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_SLP1">Sheldon</persName>]:</p>
                            <p>No. 572. Your 466, Department’s 7707, May 12, 2.45 p.m. [<hi rend="italic">May 11, 7 p.m.</hi>] I am informed that there is
                                some prospect of the Dutch being willing to reopen negotiations for
                                a general agreement and have asked the Foreign Office what news they
                                have on this point. If this proves to be the case think it would be
                                unwise to start independent negotiations regarding Dutch colonial
                                trade. The Foreign <pb facs="0656" n="1490" xml:id="pg_1490"/>
                                Office has suggested that I telegraph you asking that you give no
                                definite declaration in regard to future requisitioning of Dutch
                                ships without consultation with them.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_PWH1">
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Page</hi>
                                    </persName>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>